    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Can I take reishi with melatonin for sleep?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Yes, reishi and melatonin work through different mechanisms and can be safely combined. Melatonin directly signals the brain to initiate sleep onset, while reishi modulates the stress response and GABAergic system to promote relaxation. Some users find that reishi reduces the dose of melatonin needed for effective sleep. Start with reishi alone for 2 weeks, then add melatonin if needed, to isolate the effects of each supplement.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'What is the difference between red reishi and other reishi varieties?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Red reishi (Ganoderma lucidum) is the most extensively studied variety and contains the highest concentrations of triterpenes and beta-glucans. Other varieties include black reishi (G. sinense), purple reishi (G. japonicum), and white reishi. Red reishi has the strongest evidence base for immune modulation, sleep support, and stress management. The vast majority of clinical research — over 400 studies indexed on PubMed — uses Ganoderma lucidum (red reishi). When purchasing reishi gummies, confirm the product uses Ganoderma lucidum specifically.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Is reishi safe to take every day?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Reishi has been consumed daily in traditional Chinese medicine for over 2,000 years and has an excellent safety profile in modern clinical trials lasting up to 16 weeks. The most commonly reported side effects are mild GI discomfort (dry mouth, stomach upset) in a small percentage of users. Reishi may have anticoagulant and blood-pressure-lowering properties — individuals taking blood thinners, antihypertensives, or immunosuppressants should consult a healthcare provider before supplementing. Pregnant and breastfeeding women should avoid reishi due to insufficient safety data.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Should I take reishi in the morning or at night?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'For sleep support, take reishi 1-2 hours before bedtime. For stress management and immune support, morning or early afternoon dosing is common. Unlike sedatives, reishi does not cause drowsiness — it promotes calm alertness during the day and better sleep architecture at night. Some users split their dose, taking half in the morning for stress resilience and half before bed for sleep quality. Consistency matters more than timing.' },
    },
  ],
};
