    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Reishi Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Does reishi mushroom actually help with sleep?</summary>
      <p>Multiple studies suggest reishi improves sleep quality without acting as a sedative. A 2012 study in the <em>Journal of Ethnopharmacology</em> found that reishi extract significantly increased total sleep time and non-REM sleep. A 2005 human trial showed significantly improved sleep quality after 8 weeks of supplementation. Reishi works through GABAergic modulation and HPA axis regulation rather than direct sedation, helping normalize sleep patterns without forcing drowsiness.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What are triterpenes in reishi and why do they matter?</summary>
      <p>Triterpenes (ganoderic acids) are the primary bioactive compounds responsible for reishi's adaptogenic, anti-inflammatory, and calming effects. Over 150 distinct triterpenes have been identified in <em>Ganoderma lucidum</em>. They modulate immune function, reduce histamine release, and support stress resilience. Products specifying triterpene content of 2-4% are generally more potent than those listing only beta-glucans.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How long does it take for reishi gummies to work?</summary>
      <p>Most users notice improved sleep quality within 1-2 weeks. Stress resilience and immune benefits typically appear after 4-8 weeks of consistent use. Reishi works through cumulative adaptogenic mechanisms, regulating the HPA axis over time. Clinical studies showing immune modulation run 8-12 weeks. Commit to a minimum of 4 weeks before evaluating effectiveness.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What dosage of reishi is clinically effective?</summary>
      <p>Clinical studies typically use 1,000-3,000mg per day of reishi fruiting body extract. For sleep and stress support, 1,000-1,500mg of dual-extracted reishi is the most commonly studied dose range. Most gummies provide 500-1,000mg per serving. Higher doses up to 5,000mg per day have been used in immune support studies without adverse effects.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can I take reishi with melatonin for sleep?</summary>
      <p>Yes. Reishi and melatonin work through different mechanisms and can be safely combined. Melatonin signals sleep onset; reishi modulates the stress response and GABAergic system to promote relaxation. Some users find reishi reduces the dose of melatonin needed. Start with reishi alone for 2 weeks, then add melatonin if needed.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the difference between red reishi and other varieties?</summary>
      <p>Red reishi (<em>Ganoderma lucidum</em>) is the most studied variety with the highest triterpene and beta-glucan concentrations. Other varieties include black, purple, and white reishi. Over 400 studies on PubMed use <em>Ganoderma lucidum</em> specifically. When purchasing reishi gummies, confirm the product uses this species.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Is reishi safe to take every day?</summary>
      <p>Reishi has been consumed daily for over 2,000 years and has an excellent safety profile in clinical trials lasting up to 16 weeks. Mild GI discomfort (dry mouth, stomach upset) is occasionally reported. Those taking blood thinners, antihypertensives, or immunosuppressants should consult a healthcare provider. Pregnant and breastfeeding women should avoid reishi due to insufficient safety data.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Should I take reishi in the morning or at night?</summary>
      <p>For sleep support, take reishi 1-2 hours before bedtime. For stress and immune support, morning or afternoon dosing works well. Reishi does not cause drowsiness — it promotes calm alertness during the day and better sleep architecture at night. Some users split their dose between morning and evening. Consistency matters more than timing.</p>
    </details>

